Initial project scope

Report on New York Stop, Question and Frisk in 2021.

Dataset briefing

  • Two datasets will be used in this report. (1) Stop, Question and Frisk data in 2021 (.xlsx file) from NYPD website; (2) Police Precincts shapefile data from NYC Open Data website.
  • The .xlsx file contains NYPD Stop Report Database in 2021. First I check this table in Excel and notice there are 83 columns which are collected in categories, including Stop, Question and Frisk (SQF) year/month/time, description of the suspect, whether the suspect was arrested or given an offense, SQF address and location, etc.
  • Notice: there are lots of binary columns in the .xlsx file, and if the content is ‘No’, it was documented as ‘(null)’ in this data. However this does not mean the cells are NA values.
  • Stop location was collected as X and Y value in the New York-Long Island State Plane Coordinate System (EPSG 2908). Unit of this projection is US survey foot, it is better to transform it into NAD83(2011) / New York Long Island (EPSG:6538) which is in metre unit.

Research background

  • “The stop-question-and-frisk program, or stop-and-frisk, in New York City, is a New York City Police Department practice of temporarily detaining, questioning, and at times searching civilians and suspects on the street for weapons and other contraband.

    In 2016, a reported 12,404 stops were made under the stop-and-frisk program. The stop-and-frisk program has previously taken place on a much wider scale. Between 2003 and 2013, over 100,000 stops were made per year, with 685,724 people being stopped at the height of the program in 2011. At this peak, over 99% of recorded non-lethal interpersonal violence in the city was committed by the New York Police Department itself.

    The program also became the subject of a racial-profiling controversy. Ninety percent of those stopped in 2017 were African-American or Latino, mostly aged 14–24. Seventy percent of those stopped were later found to be innocent.” (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stop-and-frisk_in_New_York_City)

Research question

  • Are innocent people who experienced SQF in 2021 for New York spatially random or do they exhibit clustering?

  • Hypothesis: there are spatial clusters for innocent people who experienced SQF in 2021 for New York.

Research design

  • Transform all the SQF data as geographical points.

  • And extract points without being arrested nor given summon (define this type of people as ‘innocent’ in this report).

  • Then use Ripley’s K and DBSCAN to find the clusters.

  • To avoid limitations in DBSCAN, use HDBSCAN for clustering, compare the results and evaluate it.

  • Compare location and number of clusters and make suggestions for policy makers.

Spatial pattern analysis.

For clustering, which method we choose depends on what characteristics our data have. In this report, the innocent points are: (1) Arbitrarily shaped clusters; (2) Clusters with different sizes and densities; (3) Noise.

K-means cluster is bad at recognising noise. Also, the irregular shape of New York city means quatrat analysis is not applicable either.

Thus, DBSCAN or HDBSCAN clustering are more appropriate for this report.

Ripley’s K

  • Use Ripley’s K to compare the observed distribution of points with the Poisson random model for a whole range of different distance radii.
K <- innocent_sp.ppp %>% 
  Kest(.,correction = 'border') %>% 
  plot()

  • Black line: observed distribution of points
  • Red line: Poisson distribution

The black and red lines nearly intersect. But there is a peak for black line (when r is nearly 3000) and a sharp rise trend before the peak point. The result shows that the innocent points throughout New York can be clustered when the distance radii is less than 3000. This provide a reference for the following epsilon in DBSCAN.

DBSCAN

library(fpc)
  • First extract the points from the spatial points data frame
innocent_df <- innocent_sp %>% 
  coordinates(.) %>% 
  as.data.frame()

Two things are most important for DBSCAN: eps (the maximum distance between two points) and minpts(minimum points)

  • From the result of Ripley’s K, I start searching the best eps from 3000, and then decrease the distances according to the cluster result.
  • As mentioned above. Choose 50 points as minpts.
innocent_df%>%
  dbscan::kNNdistplot(.,k=50)
abline(h = 3000, lty = 2) #showing the elbow point in the graph.

From the plot above, 3000 again seems like a good distance for clustering.

However, at this distance, nearly everything merges into one cluster, which indicates that eps number should be smaller.

After trying for several numbers, 1000 seems like a good distance for clustering.

db <- innocent_df %>%
  fpc::dbscan(.,eps =1000, MinPts = 50)
plot(db, innocent_df, 
     main = "DBSCAN Output", frame = F)
plot(ny_proj$geometry, add=T)

Mapping DBSCAN result.

innocent_df<- innocent_df %>%

HDBSCAN

As mentioned above, the eps value I chose is not completely convincing (based on observation of the output). To avoid this problem, it is better to use HDBSCAN, which does not reply on the eps input because it chooses the clusters automatically.

library(dbscan)

  • Comparison.

HDBSCAN and DBSCAN both show three large clusters in Bronx, Manhattan and central Brooklyn. However, comparing to DBSCAN output, HDBSCAN recognizes more clusters distributed in other boroughs in New York. While in DBSCAN, when the distance becomes smaller, the clusters in the Staten island and Queens area are ignored..

Thus, HDBSCAN presents a more complete picture at the scale of New York City.

Interpretation:

  • How are the clusters spatially distributed:

The cluster map shows there are 9 clusters for innocent people who experienced Stop, Question and Frisk in New York in 2021.

Two huge clusters(cluster 6 and cluster 7) on the north are within Manhattan and Bronx, showing large groups of innocent people experienced SQF in these area. Another huge cluster is at the central of Brooklyn (cluster 9).

Four smaller clusters (cluster 3,4,5,8) are located surrounding cluster 9. Moreover, two clusters are respectively on the Staten island and the southern island of Queens.

  • Why these points exhibit clusters in these areas:

The analysis tells of a spatial clustering of people stopped without actually committing crimes. Manhattan, the bronx and central Brooklyn need to be given special attention as the clusters are much bigger.

Here I put up some possible explanations for this phenomenon. These locations can be highly dangerous and therefore police need to be more rigorous in searching everyone who is suspected. These clusters may be located in central business districts with high population density, high population mobility and high crime rates.

However, if the police acted inappropriately and were too strict about searching people, then the precincts where these clusters are located need to be further examined.

Does race and income or the appearance of the suspect have an impact on whether or not they are stopped and searched. Are there more black or minority ethnic people in these clusters, or do people in these locations have lower income levels? These are some of the things that this report brings to mind.

Reflection

  • Reflections on the methods in this report.

    1. For a better comparasion of the observed distribution of points with the Poisson random mode, I could also try Adjusted Ripley’s
    2. Although I apply HDBSCAN to adjust the results of DBSCAN, there still are a lack of evaluation of the output of HDBSCAN. And this report fails to compare these two clustering model in a more scientific way.

  • Reflections on the dataset I use.

    This dataset contains data only for 2021, which means it is quite special, not universal. In particular, 2021 is the second year of the covid pandemic and the epidemic is not completely over, with mutated viruses continuing to be prevalent in this year. Also, this report lacks an analysis of the US political context at this time (US elections). Therefore, it is likely that there are some unusual impacts of this year (for example, covid increased the gap between rich and poor, led to a rise in crime rate in some places).

  • Reflections on the research itself.

    This report looks at people who have not committed a crime but have experienced SQF (in this report, described as “innocent”). However, this definition ignores the fact that there are potential suspects (people who are armed but have not yet committed a crime) who may have been alerted to the fact that they have been searched and thus decide not to commit a crime. These people are not technically “innocent”. In future research, further detailed studies on these huge spatial clusters are needed, as well as the exploration of the issue of spatial regression and to mitigate the limitations of this report.
